We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the City Accountant to:
a. Review/analyze prior year’s transactions to identify the discrepancies and take up the necessary adjustments to correct the balances of the intra/inter-agency accounts and RPT-related accounts;
b. prepare a subsidiary ledger per individual account based on certified list of real property taxpayers and henceforth, regularly reconcile the balance of RPT/SET Receivable accounts with the list of taxpayers with paid/unpaid real property tax dues maintained by the City Treasurer then draw journal entry vouchers to adjust the balances thereof;
c. conduct regular periodic review and reconciliation of reciprocal accounts and effect adjustments of reconciling items to prevent existence of long outstanding unadjusted reconciling items;
d. effect the necessary adjustments as a result of reconciliation in the proper accounts; and
e. henceforth, maintain subsidiary records to support the general ledger accounts.

We also recommended that the City Treasurer closely coordinate with the City Assessor in generating a certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year as basis of the City Accountant for the set-up of RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred Credits at the beginning of the year.

We reiterate our recommendations that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the:
a. Inventory and Disposal Committee, in coordination with concerned Office Heads, to review the requirements and follow COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of PPEs and COA Circular No. 2015-008 in order to have a verifiable data on the existence, condition and accountability of the City’s PPEs;
b. Inventory and Disposal Committee to (i) continue the City’s inventory-taking of all properties and henceforth, submit the RPCPPE including the Report on Physical Count of Local Road Network System with detailed information in the prescribed format; (ii) in coordination with CGSO Head, to prepare and submit the IIRUP as basis in recording the de-recognition from the books of the unserviceable properties including motor vehicles, and immediately facilitate the disposal thereof to prevent further deterioration pursuant to Section 79 of P.D. No. 1445;
c. CGSO Head and City Accountant in coordination with the City Engineer, Treasurer and Assessor to maintain complete and updated records of Property Cards (PC) and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC), respectively, for all PPE accounts per asset category including Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its component under the City’s jurisdiction and Real Property Ledger Card for Land; and
d. City Accountant to (i) make the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts on the lots and motor vehicles acquired in CYs 2015-2017 and CYs 2018-2019 totaling ₱17,280,000.00 and ₱43,385,232.05, respectively; and (ii) reconcile the balances of the PPE ledger accounts with the PPELC as of year-end, draw the necessary correcting entries for any errors and/or omissions found, and prepare the PPELC for the other seven PPE accounts as required.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the CHRMO to:
a. prepare and issue policy guidelines to address the issues on the necessity and propriety of hiring Job Order employees consistent/aligned with Section 77 of R.A. No. 7160 or Local Government Code and Section 2, Rule IX of the Revised Omnibus Rules Implementing Book V of Executive Order No. 292, and Section 1 of Civil Service Commission (CSC) Resolution No. 020790 and Commission on Audit (COA), and the Department of Budget and Management (DBM) Joint Circular (JC) No. 2, S. 2020;
b. initiate the conduct of review of the City's existing Organization Structure/Plantilla in order to properly identify and establish the appropriate human resource complement, and create additional permanent position which may be considered for regular functions of the agency; and select among the qualified City's Job Order employees those who are qualified to fill the vacant permanent or casual positions;
c. limit the number of Job Order personnel based on necessity of services, qualifications and performance; and conduct periodic performance evaluation and assessment of Job Order personnel to avoid wastage of government funds; and
d. coordinate with the City Accountant in the submission of copy of JOs Approved Contracts and Monthly Accomplishment Reports to the COA Audit Team to verify the necessity and veracity of their services.

(a)  BAC to (i) require every offices/end user units to prepare PPMP then consolidate the PPMP  for the preparation of APP incorporating the procurement projects  to be undertaken thru negotiated procurement modality during a state of the public health emergency; (ii) Ensure that all POs and other notion of deliveries are adequately prepared and all necessary information  pertaining to purchases especially the brand name/specification are indicated in the POs and RIS and Furnish  the Audit team either printed copy or online/electronic copies of POs within five(5) working days upon issuance thereof; 
(b) Oversight Committee to utilize a sound warehouse management system that will streamline the receipt, packaging and distribution processes of relief packages and install an internal control mechanism to safeguard the relief goods from possible thief, loss and wastage; and 
(c) City Accountant to ensure the adequate documentation of transactions on the receiving barangay(end-users) of the packages

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the:
concerned City officials to meticulously and judiciously plan actions to be taken during occurrence of calamity;
BAC to require every office/end-user unit to prepare the PPMP and consolidate the same in the Annual Procurement Plan;
concerned officials and employees involved in the procurement of COVID-19-related ancillary supplies and materials to adopt and comply with the rules and regulations in the use of Negotiated Procurement instead of using cash advances;
General Service Officer to (i) accept first the deliveries of items purchased before distributing the same to end-user offices; (ii) prepare and maintain stock cards for the purchased supplies; and (iii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation; and
City Accountant, to (i) ensure that all purchases of supplies and materials, including donations, are recorded under the proper inventory account; and (ii) prepare supplies ledger cards for delivered items as called for in the above-quoted regulation.

5.29. 	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
instruct concerned Office Heads to review the requirements and follow COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of PPEs and COA Circular No. 2015-008 in order to have a verifiable data on the existence, condition and accountability of the City’s PPEs;
reconstitute an Inventory Committee with adequate number of members, to include at least one member each from the City Accounting and City General Services Office (CGSO) of the LGU pursuant to Item 5.2. of COA Circular 2020-006 to address the perennial issues on the establishment of the accuracy of the PPE balances particularly on the reconstruction of property records and inventory-taking of all properties of the City and henceforth, submit the RPCPPE with complete information and in the prescribed format;
direct the CGSO, in coordination with the City Accountant and the City Engineer, to maintain Property Cards for all PPE accounts per asset category including complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its component under the City’s jurisdiction; and
require the City Accountant to submit the (i) Latest Declaration of Real Property of lots purchased; and (ii) copies of Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) reflecting the take-up of donated patrol vehicles from the 20 agency-recipients; and prospectively, ensure compliance with the regulations on donated/transferred assets.
5.30. 	Further, we reiterated our previous recommendations that the LCE require the:
a. 	City Accountant, in coordination with the City Treasurer, to (i) exert effort to verify the existence and ownership of real properties reported by the City Assessor and reconcile these with the Land Account reflected in the books and make the necessary adjustments; and (ii) thereafter, prepare and maintain Real Property Ledger Cards for Land in compliance with Section 120 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs;
b. 	City Treasurer, together with the City Accountant and the City Assessor to (i) cause the proper titling of the owned lots in the name of the City Government; and (ii) come up with fair value of lands owned by the City but still unrecognized in the Books owing to lack of basis for valuation purposes;
c. 	City Accountant to draw the necessary correcting entries for any errors and/or omissions found in the PPE accounts with variance of ₱249,271,678.52 and to prepare the PPELC for the seven PPE accounts;
d. 	City Accountant to make the necessary adjustments in the books on the acquired motor vehicles in CYs 2018-2019 totaling ₱43,385,232.05; and
e. 	City General Services Officer/Head to prepare and submit the IIRUP as basis in recording the de-recognition in the books of the unserviceable properties and immediately facilitate the disposal of the unserviceable motor vehicles including other properties to prevent further deterioration of the same pursuant to Section 79 of P.D. No. 1445.
5.31. 	Management agreed to comply with the audit recommendations and reconstituted the Inventory and Disposal Committee through the issuance of Executive Order (E.O) No. 128 dated May 12, 2022 as part of the compliance.

7.22. 	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the CHRMO to:
prepare and issue policy guidelines to address the issues on the necessity and propriety of hiring Job Order employees consistent with the provisions of Civil Service Commission (CSC), Commission on Audit (COA), and Department of Budget and Management (DBM) Joint Circular (JC) No. 2, S. 2020;
initiate the conduct of review of the City’s existing Organizational Structure/Plantilla in order to properly identify and establish the appropriate human resource complement and create additional permanent positions which may be considered for regular functions of the agency; and select among the qualified City’s Job Order employees to fill the vacant permanent or casual positions;
limit the number of Job Order personnel based on the necessity of services, qualifications and performance; and conduct periodic performance evaluation and assessment of Job Order personnel to avoid wastage of government funds; and
coordinate with the City Accountant in the submission of the JO’s approved Contracts and Accomplishment Reports to the COA Audit Team in order to verify the necessity and veracity of their services.

9.20.     We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the:
Bids and Awards Committee Chairman/Head Secretariat, in coordination with the City Budget Officer, to submit the City’s Annual Procurement Plan (APP) including Project Procurement Management Plan and strictly observe the regulations prescribed by the Revised IRR of R.A No. 9184;
BAC Secretariat Head, in coordination with General Services Office Head, to furnish the COA Audit Team with copies of all Purchase Orders and Perfected Contracts, including supporting documents, and the Notice of Delivery as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2009-001, COA Circular No. 96-010 and COA Circular No. 95-006, respectively;
City Engineer to ensure that the required information posted in the Project Billboard/Signboard are complete and to strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 on posting of PPAs; and
Bids and Awards Committee, through the Head Secretariat, to strictly comply with Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 of the Revised IRR of R.A No. 9184 on the posting of Notice of Award, Notice to Proceed and Approved Contract in the PhilGEPS.
9.21. 	Management agreed to comply with the audit recommendations. The City Budget and BAC Offices have committed to submit the CY 2022 Annual Procurement Plan (APP) and Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP). Also, the CGS Officer, in his reply, cited that the CGSO is closely coordinating with the City Accounting Office to efficiently and effectively discharge its function to help improve the City’s procurement process.

10.16	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
a. 	City Accountant in coordination with the Head-BAC Secretariat to (i) submit the above-cited requisite documents; and (ii) ensure that the required documents including all other required data/information particularly for the procurement of goods are complete before processing and payment;
b. 	Bids and Awards Committee, through the Head Secretariat, to strictly comply with Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 of the Revised IRR of R.A No. 9184 on the posting of Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed and Approved Contract in the PHILGEPS, respectively;
c. 	GSO Head to strictly comply with the provisions of the Manual particularly on the acceptance and inspection of goods; and
d. 	Chief Accountant, in coordination with the GSO Head, to coordinate with the Mabalacat City Schools Division OIC Superintendent/Head to get a copy of the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) reflecting the recognition of donated items/equipment; and prospectively, ensure compliance with the regulations on donated/transferred assets.
10.17. 	Management agreed to comply with the audit recommendations. The CGS and BAC Offices assured the Audit Team of compliance with the above cited provisions of R.A. No. 9184. Also, the BAC has committed in the submission of periodic reports to the Audit Team.

a. City Budget Officer to (i) adequately appropriate in its annual budget no less than five percent (5%) of the estimate revenue from regular sources as LDRRMF; (ii) Ensure that the transfer of appropriations from one item to another are within the same expense class of their respective appropriations in consonance with Section 336 of R.A No. 7160; and (iii) in such case of budgetary realignment especially in times of public calamity; ensure that an enacted Appropriation Ordinance are certified under oath jointly by the local treasurer and local accountant by the LCE;

b. CDRRMO head to (i) prepare the annual LDRRM investment Plan and subject to further amendments, if the need arises, particularly in the case of public health threats;

c. Refrain from charging ineligible expenditures classified as regular operating expenses to the LDRRMF and ensure that funds are used in accordance with Section 21 of R.A No. 10121 and Item 4.3 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2014-1; and

d. City Accountant, Budget Officer   and Treasurer to coordinate with one another to (i) establish the remaining unutilized balance of the LDRRMF based on the realized income from regular sources and compute for the unutilized balance backed up by cash for transfer to the special TF; and (ii) thereafter, fully disclosed in the Notes to Financial Statements the details of the unexpected LDRRMF balance of previous years accrued to special TF under the account “ Trust Liability-DRRM” and maintained the SLs thereon.

(a) Work on the immediate liquidation of cash advanced as soon as the purposes of the grant have already been served;

b) Expedite the completion and submission of the documentary deficiencies or requirements including distribution list or its equivalent of procured rice and food items to the Audit Team, and 

(c)Ensure the completeness of the require supporting documents for every transaction and provide all the require data/information before any payment is made.

a. City Accountant and City Treasurer to liquidate the SAP-1 and return the unutilized funds to the DSWD;

b. City Accountant and Gender and Development (GAD) Officer to submit the SAC Forms anf photo of beneficiaries during the actual distribution of SAP-1; and

