a. City HRMO head to (i) cause the refund of excess employer’s contribution for the current year;

b. City Budget Officer to maintain the require registries to prevent incurrence of expenditures in excess of allotments or budget overrun; and

c. City Accountant to (i) invariably support the disbursements of PAG-IBIG premiums of JO employees with certified copies of proofs of remittances by the City including all other corresponding schedules thereof.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the: 

(a) City Health Office and City Pharmacist, along with other health unit officials, to maintain (i) Stocks Inventory Report which shows the quantity of medicines received, the complete description of medicines received, the quantity of medicines utilized within a month, and balance of medicines in quantity per item at the end of the month; (ii) Utilization Report which shows the complete name of patient, date of visit, complete address, age, gender, health complaints of patient, diagnosis, complete description and quantity of dispensed medicines; (iii) Monthly Summary of Medicines Utilized which shows the quantity of medicines dispensed to patients taken from Utilization Report and complete description of medicines; (iv) Annual Inventory Report which shows the quantity of medicines remaining in stocks as of year-end and complete description of per items of medicines; (v) install an inventory monitoring mechanism to monitor the expiration of medicines;

(b) City Accountant to recognize all purchases of drugs and medicines in the books using the Inventory account and use the Monthly Summary of Medicines Utilized prepared by the CHO as basis in the recognition of utilized medicines under the Drugs and Medicines Expense account.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive together with the City Human Resource Management Officer: 

(a) prepare and issue policy guidelines to address the issues on the necessity and propriety of hiring job orders in order to limit the expenditures to programs/projects that are highly essential to merit the recruitment of the same; 

(b) hire job order personnel based on necessity and skills/competencies and who should be identified/attributed to specific local projects authorized by the Sanggunian for a period not exceeding six months; 

(c) avoid the hiring of job orders whose functions overlap/duplicate those of the regular employees of the City; 

(d) comply with submission of the Contract of Service, Accomplishment Reports and copy of government issued valid IDs to evaluate the necessity and validity of all JO personnel employed as of December 31, 2017 especially those 873 who did not appear for interview; and 

(e) rationalize the daily rates of those whose designations are similar yet are paid with different rates.

We also recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) recover the amount of ₱52,057.00 from those persons deemed liable for the inclusion of inexistent individuals in the JO payroll and the receipt of their salaries, based on the result of an investigation by the City Legal Officer or appropriate Office;

(b) if warranted, file appropriate charges against officials and employees who conspired with the payroll fraud for JOs; 

(c) install control procedures to cleanse the JO payrolls of inexistent individuals and to forestall the commission of payroll fraud.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

(a) request the Sanggunian Panlungsod to revisit the Mabalacat City Passenger Terminal Code of 2013 and request the inclusion of protective provisions to address the issues on internal control, audit and examination of the books of the JV and the reportorial responsibilities of the Joint Venture Board (JVB) in supporting the computations on the City’s share from the JV; 

(b) require the Management Team of the JV or JVB to submit monthly reports duly certified/signed by the proper signatories showing the detailed computations of share from JV remitted to the City Treasurer;  

(c) instruct the supervisor of the City employees assigned at the MCPTC to submit to the City Accountant the copies of duly certified daily lists of buses entering the said terminal complex, including information on the first and last control numbers/series per booklet of terminal tickets/receipts issued by the cashiers within the day;  

(d) instruct the City Accountant to assign an Accounting Staff to monitor the submission of the duly certified daily lists of buses entering the terminal complex and to review the completeness and accuracy thereof; 

(e) require the Management Team of the JV/JVB to (i) submit monthly statement of accountability for accountable forms which shows the control number/series of terminal tickets/receipts purchased and issued within the month and balance of unused tickets/receipts at the end of the month; and (ii) to support with reasonable documentations the monthly check/cash disbursements for authorized expenditures to establish their validity and propriety; and 

(f) require the JVB to (i) register the JV with the Securities and Exchange Commission pursuant to the NEDA guidelines on JV with private entities dated May 3, 2013; and (ii) issue BIR-compliant tickets/receipts to the public utility buses using the terminal complex and passengers using the comfort rooms pursuant to Section 3 of BIR Revenue Regulations no. 18-2012 dated October 22, 2012.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) address with urgency the manpower issues faced by the City Accounting Office; 

(b) require the City Accountant and the City Treasurer to improve compliance (i) in the rendition of accounts and financial reports in order not to delay the verification and audit of transactions and the recording of transactions in the appropriate period; and (ii) in the submission to the Audit Team of the required financial reports and documents within the prescribed; 

(c) enjoin all officers and offices concerned to comply with the submission of adequate documents before forwarding any claim to the Accounting Office for processing.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the: 

(a) City Budget Officer to provide information on the budget allotment of the five projects dropped from the amended 20% DF for the evaluation of the Audit Team and to establish the proper accounting thereof in the books; 

(b) City Engineer and the City Planning and Development Officer to (i) comply with the reportorial and monitoring requirements as prescribed in the COA Circular 2013-004 on the submission of Quarterly Report of the Publicized Government Projects/Programs/Activities on Infrastructures; (ii) improve the level and quality of monitoring on  the status of project implementation, including the preparation and submission of  regular status reports,  so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time; (iii) along with the LDC, improve the optimization of 20% DF thru early planning and compliance with the guidelines on the utilization of the DF under DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1 and (vi) consider endorsing alternative priority programs to replace the cancelled ₱21.95 million Rehabilitation of Quitangil project for approval of the LDC and the Sanggunian Panlungsod.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the: 

(a) City Accountant to prepare timely quarterly and annual SEF Utilization Reports pursuant to Item 6 of DepEd, DBM, DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 dated January 19, 2017 for submission to the City Local School Board and the Audit Team; 

(b) Members of the City Local School Board to (i) regularly monitor the utilization of SEF budget using the SEF Utilization Report prepared the by City Accountant; (ii) as far as feasible, cause the implementation of high-impact SEF PPAs at the earliest time of the year for the completion thereof within the same year; (ii) implement the SEF PPAs in the 1st quarter of every year for the early procurement of infrastructure projects and other capital outlay PPAs in order to avoid delays in implementation;  (iii) evaluate the causes of the non-implementation of four SEF PPAs amounting to ₱10,502,179.10 in order to gain lessons or inputs therefrom; and (iv) closely adhere to the provisions of Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 dated January 19, 2017 of the DepEd, DBM and DILG in the preparation of the SEF budget and in the utilization thereof.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
continue to mobilize the Inventory Committee to (i) formulate concerted efforts to expedite the reconstruction of PPE records and to diligently carry-out their duties and functions as mandated in Executive Order No. 72, s. 2018; (ii) in coordination with the City Engineer, conduct an inventory of the local roads under the City’s jurisdiction; (iii) prepare and submit the comprehensive Report on the Physical Count of PPE duly reconciled with the accounting and property records; (iv) verify the disposition of its unserviceable properties  and set the final appraised value of unserviceable properties for the preparation of Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP); and (iv) exhaust every means to locate the whereabouts of vehicles not presented during the physical count and exert efforts to determine accountable persons for the lost/unaccounted items and initiate administrative, civil or penal action, as warranted by the results of investigation;
instruct the General Service Officer to maintain Property Cards for all PPE accounts per category, a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its component under the City’s jurisdiction;
instruct the City Engineer, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, to come up with a complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects under the City’s jurisdiction;
direct the City Accountant to have updated PPE General Ledgers supported with PPE Ledger Cards; and Road Networks General Ledger supported with Local Road Network Ledger Cards; and
as soon as the comprehensive Report on the Physical Count of PPE becomes available, instruct the City Accountant and the City Engineer to determine the components of local roads identified in the said report without corresponding cost and recognize the cost of each component at its fair value.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:
the LDC and other concerned department to formulate 20% DF programs, projects and activities which are aligned and in accordance with the City’s priority programs, projects and activities as embodied on its LDIP/CDP and monitor and execute accordingly based on the timeline provided thereto;
City Budget Officer to submit the (i) Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations for Continuing Appropriations for CY 2017 and onwards; (ii) SP resolution for the specific projects on lump-sum appropriations under the 20% DF and refrain from charging ineligible projects which are not appropriated thereto;
City Accountant to render the submission of all 20% DF disbursement vouchers; and
City Engineer and the City Planning and Development Officer to (i) comply with the reportorial and monitoring requirements as prescribed in DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2008-156 on submission of Annual/End-of-Term Accomplishment Report for all AIP and LDIP programs/projects; (ii) improve the level and quality of monitoring on  the status of project implementation, including the preparation and submission of  regular status reports on issues and concerns affecting the delayed execution of the projects,  so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time; and (iii) along with the LDC, improve the optimization of 20% Development Fund thru early planning and compliance with the guidelines on the utilization of the DF under DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the:
City Budget Officer to reduce the budget for the Ms. Mabalacat beauty pageant to ₱1 million in the next budget preparation so as to avoid being considered excessive;
City Accountant, in coordination with other concerned departments, to submit the following documents:
Acknowledgement Receipts for the 13 pairs of foot wear and 13 pieces of swim wear distributed to the candidates;
Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) related to the purchase of clothes for the candidates;
Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for the purchased clothes stored at City Wardrobe;
Program of Works and Engineering Design for the construction and repairs of modular stage; and
Acknowledgement Receipts for Equipment (ARE) for the newly-constructed units of modular stage and for existing ones.
City Accountant to (i) make necessary adjustments to record the modular stage in the appropriate PPE accounts; (ii) henceforth, to require Official Receipts for all payments made to professionals such as artists, singers, etc.; and
City General Services Officer to (i) maintain logbook for the clothes at the City Wardrobe and for the modular stage; (ii) conduct yearly inventory/ physical count; and (iii) prepare inventory reports thereof in order to protect them from theft and loss.

