City Planning and Development Officer (CPDO) to continue with the development and completion of the CBMS as source of GAD database in time for the next GAD Plan and Budget preparation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

(a) refrain from extending financial assistance to MAGEA and strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular 2007-001 dated October 25, 2007 especially in providing financial assistance only to non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and/or people’s organizations (POs); 

(b) advise the MAGEA officers and the City’s Legal Officer to revisit/revise the Collective Negotiation Agreement (CNA) with Mabalacat Government Employees Association (MAGEA) to harmonize all provisions with the Amended Rules and Regulations of Executive Order No. 180 dated June 1, 1987; 

(c) submit the revised CNA to the Civil Service Commission – Personnel Relations Officer for registration and review to determine the non-negotiable or unenforceable items in the said agreement before enforcing it; 

(d) refrain from extending additional benefits to employees with no firm basis even if funded/disbursed through other means like financial assistance to MAGEA; and 

(e) require the MAGEA to refund the ₱1,125,000.00 illegally disbursed in CY 2016 and ₱373,000.00 in February 2017.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

(a) address with urgency the manpower issues faced by the City Accounting Office; 


(b) require the City Accountant and the City Treasurer to (i) strictly comply with the regulation on the rendition of accounts and financial reports in order not to delay the verification and audit of transactions and the recording of transactions in the appropriate period; and (ii) observe the due dates in the submission to the Audit Team of the required financial reports and documents;  

(c) enjoin all officers and offices concerned to comply with the submission of adequate documents before forwarding any claim to the Accounting Department for processing.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

(a) request the Sanggunian Panlungsod to revisit the Mabalacat City Passenger Terminal Code of 2013 and request the inclusion of  protective provisions to address the issues on internal control, audit and examination of the books of the JV and the reportorial responsibilities of  the Joint Venture Board (JVB) in supporting the computations on the City’s share from the JV; 

(b) accept only reports from Management Team of the JV or JVB that are duly certified/signed by the proper signatories; 

(c) instruct the supervisor of the City employees assigned at the MCPTC to submit to the City Accountant the copies of duly certified daily lists of buses entering the said terminal complex, including information on the first and last control numbers/series per booklet of terminal tickets/receipts issued by the cashiers within the day; 

(d) instruct the City Accountant to assign an Accounting Staff to monitor the submission of the duly certified daily lists of buses entering the terminal complex  and to review the completeness and accuracy thereof; 

(e) require the Management Team of the JV/JVB to 

(i) submit monthly statement of accountability for accountable forms which shows the control number/series of terminal tickets/receipts purchased and issued within the month and balance of unused tickets/receipts at the end of the month; and

(ii) to support with reasonable documentations the monthly check/cash disbursements to establish their validity and propriety; and 

(f) require the JVB to 

(i) register the JV with Securities and Exchange Commission pursuant to the NEDA guidelines on JV with private entities  dated May 3, 2013; and 

(ii) issue BIR-compliant tickets/receipts to the public utility buses using the terminal complex and passengers using the comfort rooms pursuant to Section 3 of BIR Revenue Regulations no. 18-2012 dated October 22, 2012.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the 

(a) City Engineer and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to invariably comply with 

(i) Section 62 of Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 requiring the issuance of Certificate of Acceptance to the contractor one year from project completion and upon submission of the warranty security by the contractor; 

(ii) Section 62.2.2.2 of the IRR of RA No. 9184 requiring the contractor to post Performance Security with an effectivity period that covers the whole duration of one year-defects liability period;

(iii) Item 2.2 of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 requiring the display of signboards at project’s locations to notify the public about the essential features/elements of said project; and 

(iv) DPWH Department Order No. 216 on the submission of copy of Diary or Log and photographic records with imprinted dates;  


(b) City Accountant, City Engineer and BAC Secretariat to submit the lacking documents as required by COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 12, 2012 and Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and 

(c) City Engineer to conduct thorough review on the computation of ABC to ensure its compliance with the latest guidelines from the DPWH.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) instruct the BAC to 

(i) subject all procurements to public bidding unless the conditions are present for the use of shopping or other alternative mode of procurement; 

(ii) comply strictly with Section 54.1 of the RIRR of RA No. 9184 on the prohibition of splitting of contracts;

(b) direct all offices concerned and the BAC Secretariat to prepare a complete and comprehensive Annual Procurement Plan containing all the requirements of the City within a year using the format prescribed by Section 3.2 of GPPB Circular No. 01-2009 dated January 20, 2009 and pursuant to the Procurement Manual for Local Government Units.
